	    	    <div id="past" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingTwo">
	    	      <div class="panel-body">
                      <p>In Summer 2015, I helped design and develop <a href="http://peerpresents.herokuapp.com">PeerPresents</a>, a website where students can give and receive real-time feedback during classroom presentations. The work is headed by <a href="http://cs.cmu.edu/~spdow">Professor Steven Dow</a>, <a href="http://replayable.net">Professor Jessica Hammer</a>, and <a href="https://www.hcii.cmu.edu/people/amy-shannon">PhD student Amy Shannon</a> at Carnegie Mellon's <a href="https://www.hcii.cmu.edu">Human-Computer Interaction Institute</a>. My summer work was part of a Research Experience for Undergraduates (REU) program supported by the <a href="http://www.nsf.gov">National Science Foundation</a>.</p>
                      
                      <p>In Summer 2014, I developed a prototype of a full-body movement analysis system for <a href="http://www.fitruvia.com">Fitruvia</a>, which helps athletes improve their game by giving them real-time feedback on their body mechanics. Separately, I created extensive documentation and testing systems for <a href="https://github.com/piantado/LOTlib">LOTlib</a>, an open-source Python library for simulating how people learn language, made by Professor <a href="http://colala.bcs.rochester.edu/people/piantadosi/">Steve Piantadosi</a>.</p>
                      
                      <p>In Summer 2013, I developed <a href="http://unsolveddatabase.org">The Unsolved Problems Database</a>, a website where people can learn about, discuss, post, and solve unsolved problems.</p>
                      
                      <p>Before college, I wrote computer programs to compose music (violin duets, string quartets and <a href="/projects/hacc">fiddle tunes</a>) in Mathematica, and submitted a paper on graph theory to the 2011 Intel Science Talent Search.</p>
